  "prompt": "How do you get over someone you never were in a relationship with?",
  "response": "Getting over someone you were never in a relationship with, often called unrequited attraction or limerence, can be tough. Here's a breakdown of strategies to help you move on:\n\n**1. Acknowledge Your Feelings and Validate Them:**\n\n*   **Don't dismiss your emotions:**  Even though you weren't \"officially\" together, your feelings were real. Acknowledge the disappointment, sadness, or even grief you might be experiencing.  Tell yourself it's okay to feel this way.\n*   **Journaling:** Write down your feelings.  This can help you process them and gain clarity.  Don't censor yourself; just let it all out.\n*   **Talk to someone:** Confide in a trusted friend, family member, or therapist.  Sharing your feelings can lighten the burden.\n\n**2. Create Distance (No Contact/Limited Contact):**\n\n*   **Physical distance:**  Minimize opportunities to see them.  Avoid places they frequent, activities you know they'll be at, etc.\n*   **Social media detox:** Unfollow, mute, or temporarily block them on social media. Seeing their posts will only prolong the longing.\n*   **Communication cut-off (or strict limitation):** This is crucial.  Stop initiating contact.  If they reach out, keep responses brief and neutral (if you need to respond at all).  Every interaction rekindles the flame.  You're not being mean; you're protecting yourself.\n\n**3.  Challenge Idealization and Fantasies:**\n\n*   **Reality check:**  We often idealize people we're attracted to, especially when the relationship exists only in our heads.  Honestly assess their flaws and imperfections.  Remind yourself of any red flags you may have overlooked.\n*   **Stop romanticizing:**  Challenge the narrative you've built around them.  Are your fantasies realistic?  Are you projecting qualities onto them that they don't actually possess?\n*   **Focus on your needs:** Ask yourself what needs you were hoping this person would fulfill.  Now, figure out how to meet those needs yourself or with the help of others.\n\n**4. Redirect Your Energy and Focus on Yourself:**\n\n*   **Self-care is paramount:**  Prioritize your physical and mental well-being.  Eat healthy, exercise, get enough sleep.\n*   **Rediscover your passions:** Re-engage in hobbies you enjoy or explore new interests.  This helps you feel good about yourself and distracts you from your unrequited feelings.\n*   **Spend time with loved ones:**  Strengthen your existing relationships with friends and family.  Their support and company can be invaluable.\n*   **Set goals:**  Focus on personal growth and achieving your goals.  This gives you a sense of purpose and accomplishment.\n*   **Therapy:** A therapist can provide coping strategies and help you understand the underlying reasons for your attachment.\n\n**5. Understand Your Patterns and Learn From the Experience:**\n\n*   **Reflect on what attracted you:**  What qualities were you drawn to?  Are these qualities you can find in other people or cultivate in yourself?\n*   **Recognize any unhealthy patterns:**  Are you repeatedly drawn to unavailable people?  Do you have a tendency to idealize others?  Understanding these patterns can help you make healthier choices in the future.\n*   **Set boundaries:**  Establish clear boundaries in your relationships to protect your emotional well-being.\n*   **Practice self-compassion:**  Be kind and patient with yourself.  Healing takes time.\n\n**6.  Embrace the Future:**\n\n*   **Be open to new possibilities:**  Don't close yourself off to new connections.  Allow yourself to meet new people and explore other potential relationships.\n*   **Focus on building healthy relationships:**  Look for relationships based on mutual respect, genuine connection, and realistic expectations.\n*   **Remember your worth:**  You deserve to be with someone who values you and reciprocates your feelings.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Time:**  There's no set timeline for getting over someone.  Be patient with yourself.\n*   **Triggers:** Be aware of things that might trigger your feelings and try to avoid them.\n*   **Relapses:**  It's normal to have moments of sadness or longing.  Don't beat yourself up about it.  Just gently redirect your focus back to your healing process.\n*   **Professional Help:** If you're struggling significantly, don't hesitate to seek professional help from a therapist or counselor. They can provide personalized guidance and support.\n\nGetting over someone you were never with is challenging, but it's definitely possible. By focusing on self-care, creating distance, challenging your fantasies, and learning from the experience, you can move on and open yourself up to a fulfilling future. Good luck!\n",
